			<div class="content" id="post-content-1270987">
									

<blockquote>
<p>The menu itself causes no compulsion to use it over other fast food menus in double-blind testing, and has shown no ability to teleport or reproduce when left alone.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This doesn't seem entirely necessary; I like the genre-awareness in &quot;Yes, we checked, it's not people. It's usually people meat but this time it's not&quot;, but that sentence there would make as much sense as saying that it most certainly does <em>not</em> smell like cinnamon.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Due to the lack of memetic effects or mobility from SCP-971, this SCP is considered Safe and requires only minimal containment procedures.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I'm not much of a fan of this sentence either. It seems self-evident.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>as scanned and printed copies of SCP-971 have the full powers of the original</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I wasn't aware that pieces of paper could have &quot;powers&quot;. Perhaps &quot;&#8230; as scanned and printed copies of SCP-971 share the same anomalous properties of the original&quot; would be a better replacement.</p>
<p>On the whole, though, I like this. It's amusing.</p>

